# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qgis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] A **GIS software program** is a computer program to support the use of a geographic information system, providing the ability to create, store, manage, query, analyze, and visualize geographic data, that is, data representing phenomena for which location is important.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] The GIS software industry encompasses a broad range of commercial and open-source products that provide some or all of these capabilities within various information technology architectures.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] The earliest geographic information systems, such as the Canadian Geographic Information System started in 1963, were bespoke programs developed specifically for a single installation (usually a government agency), based on custom-designed data models.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Perhaps the first general-purpose software that provided a range of GIS functionality was the Synagraphic Mapping Package (SYMAP), developed by Howard T.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Fisher and others at the nascent Harvard Laboratory for Computer Graphics and Spatial Analysis starting in 1965.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] While not a true full-range GIS program, it included some basic mapping and analysis functions, and was freely available to other users.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] During the late 1970s, several of these modules were brought together into Odyssey, one of the first commercial complete GIS programs, released in 1980.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] During the late 1970s and early 1980s, GIS was emerging in many large government agencies that were responsible for managing land and facilities.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Particularly, federal agencies of the United States government developed software that was by definition in the public domain because of the Freedom of Information Act, and was thus released to the public.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] These formed the foundation of the open source GIS software community.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] The 1980s also saw the beginnings of most commercial GIS software, including Esri ARC/INFO in 1982; Intergraph IGDS in 1985, and the Mapping Display and Analysis System (MIDAS), the first GIS product for MS-DOS personal computers, which later became MapInfo.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] These would proliferate in the 1990s with the advent of more powerful personal computers, Microsoft Windows, and the 1990 U.S. census, which raised awareness of the usefulness of geographic data to businesses and other new users.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Several trends emerged in the late 1990s that have significantly changed the GIS software ecosystem leading to the present, by moving in directions beyond the traditional full-featured desktop GIS application.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] The emergence of object-oriented programming languages facilitated the release of component libraries and application programming interfaces, both commercial and open-source, which encapsulated specific GIS functions, allowing programmers to build spatial capabilities into their own programs.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Third, as the World Wide Web emerged, web mapping quickly became one of its most popular applications; this led to the development of Server-based GIS software that could perform the same functions as a traditional GIS, but at a location remote from a client who only needed a web browser installed.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] All of these have combined to enable emerging trends in GIS software, such as the use of cloud computing, software as a service (SAAS), and smartphones to broaden the availability of spatial data, processing, and visualization.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] The modern GIS software ecosystem includes a variety of products that may include more or less of these capabilities, collect them in a single program, or distribute them over the Internet.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] A desktop GIS program provides a full suite of capabilities, although some programs are modularized with extensions that can be purchased separately.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Thus, the client typically accesses server capabilities using a normal web browser.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] , only including the output phase, but current server GIS provides the full suite of functions.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] that provides a focused set of documented functions, which software developers can incorporate into their own programs.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] that include many of the management and analysis functions of GIS.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] This enables database managers and programmers to perform GIS functions without traditional GIS software.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] The current software industry consists of many competing products of each of these types, in both open-source and commercial forms.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Many of these are listed below; for a direct comparison of the characteristics of some of them, see Comparison of geographic information systems software.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] The development of open source GIS software has—in terms of software history—a long tradition with the appearance of a first system in 1978.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Numerous systems are available which cover all sectors of geospatial data handling.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Apart from desktop GIS, many other types of GIS software exist.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Note: Almost all of the companies below offer Desktop GIS and WebMap Server products.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Some such as Manifold Systems and Esri offer Spatial DBMS products as well.
[src:qgis/geographic-information-system-software] Many suppliers are now starting to offer Internet based services as well as or instead of downloadable software and/or data.
[src:qgis/geoserver] In computing, **GeoServer** is an open-source server written in Java that allows users to share, process and edit geospatial data.
[src:qgis/geoserver] Designed for interoperability, it publishes data from any major spatial data source using open standards.
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer has evolved to become an easy method of connecting existing information to virtual globes such as Google Earth and NASA World Wind as well as to web-based maps such as OpenLayers, Leaflet, Google Maps and Bing Maps.
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer functions as the reference implementation of the Open Geospatial Consortium Web Feature Service standard, and also implements the Web Map Service, Web Coverage Service and Web Processing Service specifications.
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer aims to operate as a node within a free and open Spatial Data Infrastructure.
[src:qgis/geoserver] Just as the Apache HTTP Server has offered a free and open web server to publish HTML, GeoServer aims to do the same for geospatial data.
[src:qgis/geoserver] Through standard protocols it produces KML, GML, Shapefile, GeoRSS, PDF, GeoJSON, JPEG, GIF, SVG, PNG and more.
[src:qgis/geoserver] In addition, one can edit data via the WFS transactional profile (WFS-T).
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer includes an integrated OpenLayers client for previewing data layers.
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer additionally supports efficient publishing of geospatial data to Google Earth through the use of network links, using KML.
[src:qgis/geoserver] Advanced features for Google Earth output include templates for customized pop-ups, time and height visualizations, and "super-overlays".
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer relies on GeoTools, a GIS library.
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer uses the Spring Framework, providing a request dispatch architecture for modules implementing OGC services.
[src:qgis/geoserver] The web administration application uses wicket, allowing extensions to contribute additional configuration screens.
[src:qgis/geoserver] The application provides a REST API implemented using the spring-mvc-framework.
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer is a web application, supporting any common servlet container (a standalone distribution is available with the Jetty (web server) as an embedded server).
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoWebCache, a Java-based caching component similar to TileCache, is bundled with GeoServer, but available separately.
[src:qgis/geoserver] Similarly, GeoServer packages GeoTools as a Java library, but it is also available separately.
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer is a longstanding application and has undergone several architectural changes.
[src:qgis/geoserver] GeoServer 1.0 was built around the STRUTS framework, with the migration to Spring and Wicket taking place for GeoServer 2.0.
[src:qgis/geoserver] Early versions of the REST API used restlet before migration to spring-mvc-framework.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] GRASS contains over 400 modules to render maps and images on monitor and paper; manipulate raster and vector data including vector networks; process multispectral image data; and create, manage, and store spatial data.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] It is licensed and released as free and open-source software under the GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:qgis/grass-gis] It runs on multiple operating systems, including OS X, Windows and Linux.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Users can interface with the software features through a graphical user interface (GUI) or by *plugging into* GRASS via other software such as QGIS.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] They can also interface with the modules directly through a bespoke shell that the application launches or by calling individual modules directly from a standard shell.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The GRASS development team is a multinational group consisting of developers at many locations.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] GRASS is one of the eight initial software projects of the Open Source Geospatial Foundation and is fiscally sponsored by NumFOCUS.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] GRASS supports raster and vector data in two and three dimensions.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The vector data model is topological, meaning that areas are defined by boundaries and centroids; boundaries cannot overlap within one layer.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] In contrast, OpenGIS Simple Features, defines vectors more freely, much as a non-georeferenced vector illustration program does.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] GRASS is designed as an environment in which tools that perform specific GIS computations are executed.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Unlike GUI-based application software, the GRASS user is presented with a Unix shell containing a modified environment that supports execution of GRASS commands, termed modules.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The environment has a state that includes parameters such as the geographic region covered and the map projection in use.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] All GRASS modules read this state and additionally are given specific parameters (such as input and output maps, or values to use in a computation) when executed.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Most GRASS modules and abilities can be operated via a graphical user interface (provided by a GRASS module), as an alternative to manipulating geographic data in a shell.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The GRASS distribution includes over 400 core modules.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Over 400 add-on modules created by users are offered on its website.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The libraries and core modules are written in C.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Other modules are written in C, C++, Python, Unix shell, or other scripting languages.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The modules are designed under the Unix philosophy and hence can be combined using Python or shell scripting to build more complex or specialized modules, by users, without knowledge of C programming.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] There is cooperation between the GRASS and QGIS projects.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Recent versions of QGIS can be executed within the GRASS environment, allowing QGIS to be used as a user-friendly graphical interface to GRASS that more closely resembles other graphical GIS software than does the shell-based GRASS interface.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Another project, JGrass, implemented in Java, combines the user-interface of uDig and algorithms in GRASS to provide hydrological and geomorphological analyses.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] GRASS has been under continuous development since 1982 and has involved a large number of federal US agencies, universities, and private companies.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The core components of GRASS and the management of integration of efforts into its releases was originally directed by the U.S.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Army - Construction Engineering Research Laboratory (USA-CERL), a branch of the U.S.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Army Corps of Engineers, in Champaign, Illinois.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] USA-CERL completed its last release of GRASS as version 4.1 in 1992, and provided five updates and patches to this release through 1995.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] USA-CERL also wrote the core components of the GRASS 5.0 floating point version.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The development of GRASS was started by the USA-CERL to meet the need of the United States military for software for land management and environmental planning.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] A key motive was the National Environmental Policy Act.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The development platform was Unix running on VAX hardware.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] During 1982 through 1995, USA-CERL led the development of GRASS, with the involvement of many others, including universities and other federal agencies.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] USA-CERL officially ceased its involvement in GRASS after release 4.1 (1995), though development had been limited to minor patches since 1993.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] A group formed at Baylor University to take over the software, releasing GRASS 4.2.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Around this time, a port of the software to Linux was made.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] In 1998, Markus Neteler, the current project leader, announced the release of GRASS 4.2.1, which offered major improvements including a new graphical user interface.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] In October 1999, the license of the originally public domain software GRASS software was changed to the GNU GPL in version 5.0.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Since then, GRASS has evolved into a powerful software suite with a wide range of applications in many different areas of scientific research and engineering.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] For example, it is used to estimate potential solar photovoltaic yield with r.sun.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] As of 2015, GRASS is used in academic and commercial settings around the world, and in many government agencies including NASA, NOAA, USDA, DLR, CSIRO, the National Park Service, the U.S.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Census Bureau, USGS, and many environmental consulting companies.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] As of 2015, the latest stable release version (LTS) was GRASS GIS 7.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] It was released in 2015, replacing the old stable branch (6.4) which was released in 2011.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] Version 7 added many new features, including large data support, a fast topological 2D/3D vector engine, powerful vector network analysis, a full temporal framework and many other features and improvements.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] As of 2025, the latest stable release version (LTS) is GRASS GIS 8.4.1.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] As of 2015, GRASS development is split into two branches: stable and developmental.
[src:qgis/grass-gis] The stable branch is recommended for most users, while the development branch operates as a testbed for new features.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS functions as geographic information system (GIS) software, allowing users to analyze and edit spatial information, in addition to composing and exporting graphical maps.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS supports raster, vector, mesh, and point cloud layers.
[src:qgis/qgis] Vector data is stored as either point, line, or polygon features.
[src:qgis/qgis] Multiple formats of raster images are supported, and the software can georeference images.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS supports shapefiles, personal geodatabases, dxf, MapInfo, PostGIS, and other industry-standard formats.
[src:qgis/qgis] Web services, including Web Map Service and Web Feature Service, are also supported to allow use of data from external sources.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS integrates with other open-source GIS packages, including PostGIS, GRASS GIS, Felt (GIS company), SAGA GIS, and MapServer.
[src:qgis/qgis] Plugins written in Python or C++ extend QGIS's capabilities.
[src:qgis/qgis] Plugins can geocode using the Google Geocoding API, perform geoprocessing functions similar to those of the standard tools found in ArcGIS, and interface with PostgreSQL/PostGIS, SpatiaLite and MySQL databases.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS is built on top of, and standard installs include, broadly-used open-source GIS format and projection conversion libraries GDAL and proj.
[src:qgis/qgis] Gary Sherman began the development of Quantum GIS in early 2002, and it became an incubator project of the Open Source Geospatial Foundation in 2007.
[src:qgis/qgis] Version 1.0 was released in January 2009.
[src:qgis/qgis] In 2013, along with release of version 2.0 the name was officially changed from *Quantum GIS* to *QGIS* to avoid confusion as both names had been used in parallel.
[src:qgis/qgis] Written mainly in C++, QGIS makes extensive use of the Qt library.
[src:qgis/qgis] In addition to Qt, required dependencies of QGIS include GEOS and SQLite.
[src:qgis/qgis] GDAL, GRASS GIS, PostGIS, and PostgreSQL are also recommended, as they provide access to additional data formats.
[src:qgis/qgis] As of 2017, QGIS is available for multiple operating systems including Mac OS X, Linux, Unix, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:qgis/qgis] There are several third-party apps that allow use of QGIS on mobile devices such as QField (Android, iOS and Windows), Mergin Maps (Android, iOS and Windows) and IntraMaps Roam (Windows).
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS can also be used as a graphical user interface to GRASS.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS has a small install footprint on the host file system compared to commercial GISs and generally requires less RAM and processing power; hence it can be used on older hardware or running simultaneously with other applications where CPU power may be limited.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS is maintained by volunteer developers who regularly release updates and bug fixes.
[src:qgis/qgis] As of 2012, developers have translated QGIS into 48 languages and the application is used internationally in academic and professional environments.
[src:qgis/qgis] Several companies offer support and feature development services.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS enables users to visualize their data using maps, charts, and diagrams while customizing the presentation with a variety of symbology choices.
[src:qgis/qgis] The capabilities for geographical analysis provided by QGIS include buffer construction, spatial querying, and geoprocessing.
[src:qgis/qgis] For more complex geographical analysis, users can additionally make use of plugins and algorithms.
[src:qgis/qgis] QGIS also makes it simple to share and publish geospatial data as maps, online services, or print maps in a variety of file formats, such as shapefiles, GeoTIFFs, and KML files.
[src:qgis/qgis] In order to prepare printed map with QGIS, Print Layout is used.
[src:qgis/qgis] It can be used for adding multiple map views, labels, legends, etc.
[src:qgis/qgis] As a free software application under GNU GPLv2, QGIS can be freely modified to perform different or more specialized tasks.
[src:qgis/qgis] Two examples are the QGIS Browser and QGIS Server applications, which use the same code for data access and rendering, but present different front-end interfaces.
[src:qgis/qgis] Detailed changelogs are available for releases 2.0 and later.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] In computing, the Open Geospatial Consortium **Web Feature Service** (**WFS**) Interface Standard provides an interface allowing requests for geographical features across the web using platform-independent calls.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] One can think of geographical features as the "source code" behind a map, whereas the WMS interface or online tiled mapping portals like Google Maps return only an image, which end-users cannot edit or spatially analyze.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The XML-based Geography Markup Language (GML) furnishes the default payload-encoding for transporting geographic features, but other formats like shapefiles can also serve for transport.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] In early 2006 the OGC members approved the OpenGIS GML Simple Features Profile.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] This profile is designed both to increase interoperability between WFS servers and to improve the ease of implementation of the WFS standard.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The OGC membership defined and maintains the WFS specification.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] Numerous commercial and open-source implementations of the WFS interface standard exist, including the open-source reference implementations GeoServer and deegree.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The OGC Implementing Products page provides a comprehensive list of WFS implementations.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The WFS specification defines interfaces for describing data manipulation operations of geographic features.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The basic Web Feature Service allows querying and retrieval of features.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] A transactional Web Feature Service (WFS-T) allows creation, deletion, and updating of features.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] A WFS describes discovery, query, or data transformation operations.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The client generates the request and posts it to a web feature server using HTTP.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The web feature server then executes the request.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The WFS specification uses HTTP as the distributed computing platform, although this is not a hard requirement.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] In the taxonomy of Web Services, WFS is best categorized as a non-RESTful RPC type service.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] A messaging system in which clients address messages to a specific node in a content hierarchy, called a topic.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] Publishers and subscribers are generally anonymous and can dynamically publish or subscribe to the content hierarchy.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The system takes care of distributing the messages arriving from a node's multiple publishers to its multiple subscribers.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] Messages are generally not persistent and will only be received by subscribers who are listening at the time the message is sent.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] A special case known as a “durable subscription” allows subscribers to receive messages sent while the subscribers are not active.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The Web Notification Service (WNS) is one of the implementation specifications for the Pub/Sub model.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] Regardless of the model, URL format is used and specified in the WFS specification.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] At this time there are no open-standard implementations of WNSs.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] Vendors plan to release implementations once the standard has been ratified.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] Data passed between a Web Feature Server and a client is encoded with Geography Markup Language (GML), an XML dialect which can be used to model geographic features.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The 1.0.0 version of the WFS specification requires the use of GML version 2.1.2, while the 1.1.0 version of the WFS specification requires the use of GML version 3.1.1.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] For both versions of the WFS specification, an arbitrary number of other encodings can also be defined, in addition to the required GML 2.1.2 or 3.1.1 format (for 1.0.0 and 1.1.0 respectively).
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] GML 2.1.2 contains encoding support for basic geometric 'primitives': points, lines, polygons, etc.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] GML 3.1.1 contains encoding support for more advanced geometric representations: curves, surfaces, multi-dimensions (time, elevation, multi-band imagery).
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] In addition, GML 3.1.1 includes encoding support for topologically integrated datasets.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The static interface model for the OGC Web Service model appears in the figure below.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] The Transaction and LockFeature operations are also optional.
[src:qgis/web-feature-service] This model uses the OGC Web Notification Service to send update notifications to registered clients.
